= [[span class="VT323" style="font-size: 1.3em;font-weight:400;"]]<BEGIN TRANSCRIPT>[[/span]]
@@ @@
[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Yes, hello?

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Hey, Ailee. It's Place.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Well, well, well. If it isn't Mr. Dr. McDoctorate. How's my old mentor-- Wait, how did you get my personal number?

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] You know. Internet.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Wh-- //uh//. What?

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] I'm just joking! Relax. I got it from Hishakaku. //<Pause, followed by a laugh.>// Okay, nope, can't say that with a straight face. 

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Are we prank calling people now? What are you, like, twelve?

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] No, sorry, sorry. It's been a day. I, uh, I tried your office, but you weren't there. Your assistant gave me this number. 

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] That's why I pay them the big bucks. Okay, so what is it, Place? I'm off the clock here.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] It's eleven in the morning. 

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Normal people take lunch breaks, it's not that weird.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Ugh, don't get me started on normal people.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] //What do you want?//

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Right. Well, I bet you've heard about the whole MAUVe situation. 

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] You mean the quarter-billion-dollar machine that disappeared off the face of the Earth thanks to a conscript //I// signed off on? Yes, I have heard about it. 

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Yes, exactly. So I was going back through the transcript of your meeting with Du and company...

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Uh-huh. I don't exactly remember too much from that meeting, you know.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Yeah, no, for sure. Anyway, there's a point where the conscript says something odd, and I wanted your take on it.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Most of what it said was odd. It also made little sense. From what I remember.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Totally, I getcha. Well, something in particular stuck out to me. Enkidu said something to the effect of, 'I simply wonder: who gave me my name?' Do you remember that?

//<Silence.>//

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] It did get me wondering as well. You were present for its conscription. If anyone would know who chose that name, it would be you, right?

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Yeah, I suppose so. Uh...

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] So, if you could let me know, it might help me get to the bottom of this.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] //<Sighs.>// Alright. I'm gonna be completely straight with you Place. We had a name picked out for it, like we usually do-- Bernard. Jaime is a huge //Westworld// fan, and we all liked the sound of it, all, except for, uh, the conscript itself. 

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Oh...? I mean, they //are// capable of having preferences, that's not super concerning or anything.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Not in isolation, sure. When we were running first-use protocols and getting the conscript set up, before we had even connected it to the network, it told us it wanted to be called Enkidu. 

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] //Oh.// Huh. That //is// unusual. Maybe it overheard one of the team, or you guys left a TV on or something? I heard about that one conscript that was left alone during a fire drill and learned all of its social skills from //The Jersey Shore//--

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] //<Flustered.>// No, it wasn't like that! I'm being serious.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Right. Well, did it give any reason why it wanted the name?

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] //<Pauses.>// No. But it was adamant. And-- //Ah//.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] What is it?

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Okay, before I tell you this, you have to understand that it passed QA with flying colors, alright? It has been a faithful and hard-working conscript for decades now. Okay?

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Uh- oh, yeah, of course. I understand. 

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Well... It was an odd one. You see, when we first started making biomechanical conscripts, we couldn't just grow brains to our specification in a lab. Nowadays, the lab-made stuff is a //lot// better, but it still is imperfect. We don't understand the brain fully so it's not surprising that we can't model one with the complete specialization we expect a human brain to have. So, back when we first started doing this, we'd, uh... //<Pauses.>// We'd use brain tissue from the recently deceased. 

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] …Alright. Good to know. Continue.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] There's a number of procedures we needed to carry out before they'd be viable. Testing for traces of psychoactives, evidence of CTEs, multiple sclerosis, tumors, et cetera. One of the procedures involves basically piecemealing certain brain structures from other cadavers. We'd try to aim for about twenty or so different people. The variety reduces any chronic issues, foreign memories, maladaptive behaviors, so on. They'd steep in some amnestic brine and we'd, very carefully, reassemble the desired structures into the conscript's cerebral interface, which it shadows for some time while developing something like human consciousness. From there, it ends up in one of two situations. Either it exists fully separate from the interface, experiencing a //generally-human// perspective, for a time, and without the fancy neurochemical bells and whistles, //or// we can install the interface into a body of some type, and allow the conscript as close to free will as we can give it. Which is just about as much as we have ourselves. 

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] And... what does this have to do with Enkidu.aic, exactly?

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Well, as I said, if it exists without the interface, it only has a facsimile of a facsimile of consciousness, and only for a limited timeframe. To upkeep them, you need to allow them to shadow the interface periodically, once every few years, or its personality matrix starts to degrade. Enkidu shadowed for maybe five minutes total. It just didn't want anything to do with it, after that.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Okay, that's not exactly great, I imagine.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Aside from this fiasco with MAUVe, it's been fine. I was extremely impressed with it at the time. If it shadowed the interface sufficiently in five minutes to last it a few dozen years with zero visible degradation, Enkidu is one of the most intelligent conscripts ever created.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Why do I feel like you don't believe that's the whole story?

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] I don't know. In light of everything it just makes me wonder if it even shadowed the interface at all. It-- It felt //sad//, Place. From the second it was active, it felt preoccupied with something. Like, yeah-- being sad. As if it was grieving. It passed all of its QA though, like I said. Cognition, logic, safeguards, self-regulation—all green across the board. Sure, it was strange, but… strange isn’t necessarily dangerous. At least, that’s what I told myself.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] You're correct. And it isn't your fault things ended up like they did. 

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] Thanks, McDoctorate. Now, if you don't mind, I'm gonna try to finish my lunch and head back onsite with my head down. Hopefully there isn't an investigation already waiting for me there. Let me know if you find anything.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. MCDOCTORATE:[[/span]] Yeah. It'll work out. Just give it time, and don't beat yourself up. Take it easy.

[[span class="bd"]]DR. LOMOND:[[/span]] You too.
@@ @@
= [[span class="VT323" style="font-size: 1.3em;font-weight:400;"]]<END TRANSCRIPT>[[/span]]
